column168: Mr David Elbert tendered total 18 pieces for transport by air from FAI to BRW. At initial inspection 1 pc found to be unacceptable hazmat. He had some knowledge of other cargo carrier who would accept hazmat, he had used before.  Reduced shipment to 17 pieces.   At time of acceptance shipper asked if any other hazmat, he responded in negative.   Shipper initialed waybill as "does not" contain DG.      After shipper departed I had opportunity to screen and visually inspect.  Noticed 2 boxes of Liquid Nails construction adhesive marked as ORM-D.  Decided to physically inspect 2 plastic tubs.  1 tub contained 3 cans of Touch n Foam Cleaner.  Flammable pressurized cans.    Shipper contacted , advised shipment would be held until cleared by FAA inspector approval to move other items to him, and confiscate hazmat.      Madelvis Cronkhite/ Lead agent AlaskaAir Cargo , Fairbanks

column168: During a routine yard check, a box truck was found to have liquid dripping from the rear door.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the truck.  A 5 gallon poly cube container had a crack in the side from a drum falling against it.  The cube was overpacked into a suitable salvage container, along with spent cleaning compound used to clean the trailer floor and pavement below.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident
column169: The container was not leaking at time of pickup but the load shifted sometime between pickup and arrival at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  The driver was cautioned to use better care when blocking and bracing the load to guard against movement in any direction.

column168: An employee noticed smoke coming from a trailer parked in the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  A response crew was summoned along with the on site fire brigade. Air monitoring was commenced and the fire brigade put out the smoking trailer in under ten minutes.  The flex bin of smoking material was removed approximately one hour later and cooled.  The contents were overpacked into a suitable salvage container and the trailer was cleaned with a suitable absorbent cleaning compound.  The shipment was then prepared for acceptance into the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipment was picked up and transported to the facility by a third party carrier (not Clean Harbors).  The shipment was not packaged in accordance with 49CFR guidelines and therefore the load shifted and caused leakage.  The material began reacting and caused the smoke and smoldering.  Both the third party carrier and generator were notified of the incident.

column168: A train crew that stopped at Hickory, PA siding to include these cars in their train, noticed a strong odor coming from one of the cars.  I, John Vergis Environmental Officer with WLE, called Specialized Professional Services out to inspect the suspect car.  When they arrived, the found car UTLX 204551 was leaking vapor from the vacuum relief device.  They removed the device and installed a plug.  The car was secured and OK for transportation.  Shortly after they left, the crew noticed another car in the same cut of cars leaking. SPSI was once again called out and they then found car UTLX 205609 also leaking from the vacuum relief device and it had to be removed and a plug installed also. They next day, WLE had MarkWest come out and inspect every car in the siding before the cars were added to a train.

column168: At approximately 1245 hours on 8/18/2015, I John Vergis, was called by the WLE Train Dispatcher who said that a train crew who was picking up cars in Hickory Siding noticed that one of the Crude Oil cars that they were to pick up, GATX 211907, was leaking from the Protective Housing on top the car.  They said product was running down the sides of the car.  They found a nearby empty spike bucket and they put under the car to contain the leak.  I immediately called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to respond.  I met them on scene and after investigation, we found that the Liquid valve was leaking from the threads at the base of the valve. We wiped down the threads to make sure that it wasn't just product spilled in the housing from loading of the car.  Once the threads were cleaned, more product started coming from the threads.  We put a wrench on the valve to see if it was loose and we were able to get one half turn out of the valve tightening it further. The leak then stopped.  We tried to remove the plug from the vapor valve to relieve pressure from the car so that we could take the liquid valve off and reseal the threads but we could not get the plug out of the valve without fear of breaking off the valve itself. We then wiped down the sides of the car so it could continue in transportation.
column169: I am not sure that this problem could have been detected prior to shipment.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: QXEA Stores in PDX received 3 COMAT boxes totaling 196 pounds on air waybill 027 LAX 1375 8426 sent as non-hazmat “tools and parts” from Horizon Air maintenance in LAX. They flew on Alaska Airlines’ nonstop flight 575/20AUG.   Upon opening a Pelican case it was discovered there was a box inside containing a part off an aircraft that should have been classified as UN3363, Dangerous goods in apparatus. The Stores employee reported this to QX Stores management who in turn alerted the DG department and QX maintenance.     So far we have learned 2 Horizon Air aircraft maintenance technicians from PDX working in LAX on aircraft N416QX removed part number 92003-9C36-1 Pump cartridge. Apparently the Pelican case had no hazmat markings or indicia and it and the 2 other boxes were taken to Alaska Air Cargo.    For reasons yet to be determined, the air waybill shows Alaska Air Cargo in LAX as the shipper.   But preliminary information indicates under 49CFR the “person who offered” were the Horizon Air maintenance technicians.
column169: Under investigation and corrective actions TBD.

column168: GATX 59161 was found in the BNSF Northtown railyard leaking vapors from the liquid valve inside the protective housing.  Upon inspection the BNSF responder found that the liquid valve was a 1/4 turn open and the secondary plug was less than tool tight.  The responder properly closed the liquid valve and tool tightened the secondary plug to remediate the leak.
column169: Ensure shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car GATX 79943 was in the railyard and reported leaking commodity from the protective housing on its side shell. Minimal ground impact from spillage was observed.  BNSF Mechanical Responders inspected GATX 79943 and determined the liquid valve flange was not properly tightened at the flange connecting to the pressure plate.  All four flange bolt nuts on the liquid valve flange fitting were properly tool tightened approximately 1/4 turn.  The released commodity had evaporated from the shell and ground upon the contract responders arrival.
column169: Ensure shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical tightness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 8/4/2015 NRC Environmental Services responded to a leaking ISO tank at the BNSF Hub Yard Located in Portland, OR. Upon arrival NRC personnel conducted an assessment on the leaking tank to verify if the tank was leaking product, where it was leaking and if the leak could be mitigated. Upon the initial assessment NRC found that there was a leak of SILBOND 40HF coming from the remote shut-off control handle on the bottom outlet foot valve. NRC personnel made an attempt to tighten the handle bolts but was not able to get the leak to stop. NRC personnel contained the valve until the product could be transferred into a new ISO tank. On 8/5/2015 NRC personnel returned to the site to transfer the product from UPTU 530065-8 to a new ISO tank UPTU 30069-0. All of the contents was successfully transferred. Both ISO tanks were resealed and released to BNSF for further disposition.
column169: Shipper should identify the incident to those in charge of loading and pre-trip inspections so they can review their procedures to prevent this from occurring in the future.

column168: Our fuel delivery truck was unloading fuel(gas) to an aboveground storage tank at a marina in Sherrills Ford, NC around 3PM on August 26,2015. The tank is located at the top of a boat ramp approximately 50 feet from the lake. A hose/line on the truck burst for unknown reasons and gas ran down the boat ramp and into a lake. It is anticipated that approx. 30-60 gallons was released. Some product vaporized and a small amount (6-10 gallons)reached the water. The majority of the fuel was absorbed by the gravel/asphalt. Some soil was contaminated along the shore and edge of the boat ramp. 911 was called and Catawba County began initial response with follow up from our spill responder. Fuel was removed with absorbent boom and a vac truck. The incident was reported to the NRC and NCDENR. Cleanup and mitigation is ongoing.

column168: AT 11:10 HOURS ON 08/22/2015 KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) TRAIN CREW REPORTED THAT COVERED HOPPER CAR NDYX 816730, CONTAINING CRUDE ZINC OXIDE, WAS LEAKING. KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT THE A-END BOTTOM DOOR WAS OPENED BY A A1/2 INCH, AND NOTICED THAT THE HOPPER CAR BEHIND NDYX 816730 HAD A DUSTING OF ZINC OXIDE. IT APPEARED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS BEING FORCED OUT OF THE A1/2 INCH OPENING DURING MOVEMENT AS THE WIND CROSSED THE DOOR OPENING.  THIS CAUSED A DUST CLOUD TO APPEAR ALERTING THE CREW OF THE LEAK. THE BOTTOM HOPPER DOOR WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAK STOPPED BY TURNING THE SPROCKET GEAR. LDEQ INDICATED THAT CLEANUP WAS NOT REQUIRED.    FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED. THE ACTUAL AMOUNT RELEASED FROM THIS CONTAINER IS UNKNOWN TO THE CARRIER. TO DETERMINE ACTUAL AMOUNT RELEASED: CONTACT THE OFFEROR TO DETERMINE ACTUAL QUANTITY IN TANK CAR AT ORIGIN (IF AVAILABLE), THEN CONTACT CONSIGNEE TO DETERMINE ACTUAL AMOUNT IN TANK CAR ONCE UNLOADED (IF AVAILABLE), AND THE DIFFERENCE WILL BE THE TOTAL AMOUNT RELEASED.    FILE NOTE: ITEM 27-AMOUNT IN PACKAGE WAS ESTIMATED BY THIS REPORT PREPARER BECAUSE THE EXACT INFORMATION IS NOT AVAILABLE TO CARRIER. SHIPPER PROVIDED BULK QUANTITY ON SHIPPING PAPER AS 1 TANK CAR, PER DOT REQUIREMENTS.

column168: While inspecting the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) Meridian, MS yard, FRA Inspector Kevin Cash took exception with GATX 69484 while KCS crews were delivering it to the MNBR.  GATX 69484 was loaded with ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S (Rosin).  The defect description included residue product on the outside of the tank car.  KCS Environmental + Hazmat dispatched a response contractor to investigate and secure the package.    Upon arriving, the contractor found rosin on the left side of the car.  Two bolts on the manway were loose.  Bolt No. 1 was loose by 2 1/2 turns and Bolt No. 2 was loose by 4 turns.  The manway gasket was evaluated and determined to be bad.  It was replaced, the manway closed and the bolts tightened too tight.  The valves in the protective housing were found to be closed but the plug in the liquid line was loose by 3 turns and the vent valve was loose by 4 turns.  The loose valves were tightened. With all closures secure, the side of the car was decontaminated.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.
column198: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY

column168: Shipment was tendered as a Goldstreak for cargo, declared as a Circuit Card.  During the cargo screening by the TSA the box alarmed.  The box was opened as part of the resolution process.  Upon opening, it was discovered a 2inch Safety Detonator was in the box.  The shipment was set to the side while we contacted the shipper.  Kevin Metzger, who tendered the shipment came back to the airport to discuss the shipment.  He said that he declared it as non-hazmat because the blasting cap was removed from the detonator.  It was determined to call TSOC, and the FSD as the shipment is part of a IED.  While we were waiting for guidance on how to proceed, Kevin had several other people from Schlumberger come to talk to us.  I asked how they normally got these items up here.  He said they come in a big batch shipment declared as hazmat via FedEx and from ANC on Northern Air Cargo (who handles FedEx to Prudhoe Bay).  He said there was a failure in another one of these, so they take one from the same manufacturing batch and send it out ASAP.  He said they normally send it out on FedEx/NAC but they weren't flying and were trying to get it out quickly.  He also said that he was IATA trained and so he knew what was hazmat and what was not.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: On 4 August 2015, Westinghouse received customs information about an inbound air shipment that originated from Hyundai Heavy Industries Company, Ltd. in South Korea, that had been transported on a cargo aircraft operated by Korean Air, and had arrived at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport. Westinghouse's comparison of the commercial invoice and packing list with the Shipper's Declaration for Dangerous Goods and the air waybill indicated that undeclared zinc powder was present in the shipment. The packing box was opened for inspection and the contents verified. Inner packages of zinc powder were found included in the shipment and were not declared on the Shipper Declaration for Dangerous Goods, not indicated on the air waybill, and not labeled on the packing box. The inner packages of zinc powder were removed from packing box and repackaged in separate boxes and were properly marked and labeled for further ground transport to final destination.

column168: (1) 55-gallon drum containing Sodium Hydroxide was punctured by a nail during transit, releasing approximately 2-3 ounces to the trailer floor. The release was immediate. column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: A 1-gallon pail of UN1263 paint fell off a pallet during transit due to improper prep for transport. The can released approximately 1 gallon of paint to the trailer floor. The spill was contained to the trailer floor and did not affect any soils, waterways or drains.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: FREIGHT WAS IN THE CARGO WAREHOUSE, WAITING TO BE PICKED UP BY FREIGHT FORWARDER'S DRIVER. FREIGHT WAS STAGED IN OUR SEGREGATED DANGEROUS GOODS AREA. WHEN THE FORKLIFT DRIVE LIFTED THE WOODEN PALLET, HE DIDN'T SEE THERE WAS ALREADY A SLIT AT THE BOTTOM OF THE BAG. HE MADE A TRAIL OF UN3077 THROUGH THE WAREHOUSE AND INTO THE DRIVER'S TRUCK. THE TRUCK DRIVER NOTICED IT AND TOLD HIM. THE TEAR AT THE BOTTOM WAS 7X3 INCHES AND STARTED POURING OUT OF THE BAG. WE ESTIMATE ABOUT 125KGS WERE RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR.  CLERK IMMEDIATELY CALLED A MEMBER OF MANAGEMENT. CORDONED OFF THE AREA, PULLED THE SDS AND AT FIRST CALLED A PROFESSIONAL CLEAN UP CREW. LATER DETERMINED IT COULD BE LOCALLY CLEANED UP WITH THE HELP OF PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  2 DAMAGED PIECES REMAIN IN THE WAREHOUSE. SHRINK WRAPPED TO PREVENT MORE SPILLAGE.
column169: A SECONDARY VISUAL INSPECTION CAN BE PERFORMED PRIOR TO THE FINAL DELIVERY OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.    BEST MANAGEMENT PRACTICE - A BAG SHOULD NOT BE USED AT ALL FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SINGLE PACKAGING.
column172: Plastic, coated with liner, for solids

column168: (2) 5-gallon pails and 3 boxes that contained (2) 1-gallon pails were crushed while in transit due to improper loading. The release of 2-gallons lasted the duration of the transit. Terminal personnel performed clean up of the release, placing the impacted materials into (2) 35-gallon drums.

While unloading freight from trailer forklift operator struck a drum that was staged in the trailer with the forkblade of his forklift slightly puncturing the drum and contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged drum.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their equipment including the forkblades to prevent these types of events from occurring.

column168: During the off-loading drums at a Clean Harbors facility, employees observed a liquid material leaking out near the lids of several drums.  Employees also noticed liquid on the floor of trailer that was thought to be rain water, but it was actually material from the drums. The drums were wiped down and the floor of the trailer was cleaned up using absorbent material.  It was determined that gaskets had deteriorated and or were missing from the drum lids. New gaskets were applied to the lids of the drums and then secured to drums.  The drums were moved and did not appear to be leaking anymore.   The drums and the spilled material that was placed in a proper container was released for transportation to the intended disposal facility.
column169: Informed the customer of the situation and reminded the customer that when securing open top drums that the gasket material needs to be attached to the lid and inspected for deterioration and be replaced as needed.

column168: At 0122 hrs. on 8/11/2015 the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) was notified that a car was venting extremely loudly in a siding between MP 112 and 110 on the Meridian Subdivision.  The KCS Environmental + Hazmat Department dispatched an emergency response contractor to investigate.  Upon arrival, the contractor found GATX 38058, a loaded CO2 car, to be leaking from the protective housing.  Air monitoring was performed throughout the night. The point of release was determined to be the rupture disk. The release stabilized shortly after when balance of liquid CO2 auto-refrigerated to a solid dry ice. The car has been isolated and spotted and is awaiting replacement of the rupture disc next week.      File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. column168: A Clean Harbors employee was loading a tote onto a van trailer.  The employee did not know that the forks on the forklift were extended beyond the base of the tote causing the forks to accidently puncture a 5 gallon pail that was staged on a pallet in front of the tote.  The 5 gallon pail was immediately overpacked into a 16 gallon poly drum and the material was cleaned up and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: To prevent recurrence is to make sure all employees operating the forklift are aware that the forks may extend out the other side of a tote or pallet and to make sure the forks are lowered to the floor before coming into contact with the pallet behind the one that is on the forks.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste in cubic yard boxes was picked up on 8-27-15 and brought back to the intermediate truck transfer facility.  The next morning, one of the boxes was found to be leaking liquid onto the concrete dock.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and transferred the contents to 55 gallon drums, along with all material used to clean the dock.  The following Monday, 2 of the remaining boxes were found to be dripping and the response crew returned to transfer the rest of the shipment into drums.  The shipment then was loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The material should never have been loaded into cubic yard boxes, nor accepted in that condition.  The waste characteristics were such that the material would become liquid when exposed to air and as a PG I material should have been shipped in drums.  The driver and all involved persons that picked up the material were retrained on proper container selection.  The generator was notified of the incident and will be billed for all response activity.

column168: At approximately 1145 hours on August 15, 2015 tank car UTLX 23451 was found to be leaking at the BNSF Gallup, NM freight car repair facility in Gallup, NM.  Liquid was confined to the sides of the car in the area of the combination housing on the top and down the sides of the car, and was estimated to have lost 2-3 gallons.  BNSF personnel inspected the valves in the combination housing and found the leak originating from the bottom of the liquid valve.  Using a wrench, each of the bolts on the liquid valve flange was tightened one full turn and the leak was stopped.  Car was wiped down and cleaned and released for service.
column169: Shipper was notified via Chemtrec and will be advised to ensure appropriate checks are made utilizing the pre-trip inspection process to ensure packages loaded with hazmat are adequately closed prior to offering into shipment.

column168: On 8/21/15 at approximately 00:02 PST, the UTLX 200074 was found with wetness on the side of the car and a small amount dripping from the car.  BNSF Hazmat responders and contractors responded to the location and found the Liquid Line flange bolts were less than tool tight resulting in spillage from the appurtenance.  The fitting was tightened appropriately and spillage was cleaned from the car and impacted soils removed and stored for future disposal pending profiling and acceptance.  There were no injuries, exposures or evacuations reported.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING DOWN OHIO ROUTE 7 NORTH, TRAVELING WEST-EAST AT APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 AM, THE DRIVER LOST CONSCIOUSNESS WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS STILL TRANSIT.  THE TRACTOR BROKE THROUGH TWO SETS OF GUARDRAILS BEFORE LEAVING THE ROADWAY AND MOMENTARILY GOING AIRBORNE.  THE TRACTOR PROCEEDED DOWN A HILL BEFORE STRIKING A SPRUCE TREE WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO ROLL CLOCKWISE.  THE SPRUCE TREE BECAME ENTANGLED WITH THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRACTOR.  IN ADDITION, THE 100-GALLON SADDLE TANK ON THE DRIVER SIDE WAS TORN FROM ITS POSITION AND THROWN INTO THE REAR WALL OF A SMALL 10'X6' BOATHOUSE IN THE PATH OF THE UNIT.  AT THAT MOMENT, THE DRIVER REPORTED REGAINING AWARENESS BEFORE HE STRUCK HIS HEAD ON THE CEILING OF THE CAB.  THE TRACTOR ENCOUNTERED A SIGNIFICANT STOPPING FORCE WHEN IT CAME INTO CONTACT WITH OTHER SPRUCE TREES GROWING NEARBY.  THE CAB OF THE TRACTOR WAS PARTIALLY CRUSHED AS A RESULT.  BEFORE COMING TO A COMPLETE STOP, THE FRONT OF THE TRACTOR CRASHED IN TO THE REAR PORTION OF THE BOATHOUSE, COLLAPSING TWO OF THE FOUR WALLS AND DAMAGING THE ROOF.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER DID NOT SEPARATE AFTER COMING TO A COMPLETE STOP, FORTY YARDS FROM WHERE IT HAD LEFT THE ROADWAY, AND TWENTY YARDS FROM THE EDGE OF THE OHIO RIVER.    THE PROPERTY OWNER WAS THE FIRST PERSON TO ARRIVE ON-SCENE, WHILE IT IS BELIEVED OTHER RESIDENTS NEARBY PLACED A CALL TO 911.  THE PROPERTY OWNER WAS INSPECTING THE DAMAGES DONE WHEN HE NOTICED THE DRIVER WALKING AROUND THE UNIT.  THE DRIVER HAD SUFFERED AN UNDETERMINED HEAD INJURY AND WAS BLEEDING.  THE PROPERTY OWNER THEN CALLED 911 AND STAYED WITH THE DRIVER.  PARAMEDICS ARRIVED ON-SCENE TO BEGIN TREATING THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO PLACE A CALL TO LYKINS DISPATCH IN ORDER TO ALERT THE COMPANY RESPONDERS BEFORE HE WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL.  COMPANY PERSONNEL RESPONDED WITH REPORTING TO THE OHIO EPA (INCIDENT #508-56-1667), THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT#1124700), THE MONROE COUNTY EMA, AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  MONROE COUNTY EMA HAD ESTABLISHED CONTACT WITH MOUNTAIN STATE ENVIRONMENTAL FOR REMEDIATION AND ASSISTANCE.  THE ROADWAY WAS TAKEN DOWN TO ONE LANE FOR A MAJORITY OF THE DAY, WITH ONLY APPROXIMATELY FIVE TO SIX HOURS WHEREBY THE ROAD WAS SHUT DOWN.    THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE ALMOST COMPLETELY UPSIDE-DOWN WHEN THE UNIT CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP, BUT THE TRAILER WAS STILL AT AN ANGLE.   THE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER COULD NOT BE RECOVERED THROUGH THE LOAD HEADS, AND SO THE DECISION TO DRILL INTO THE BARREL WAS CONCLUDED TO BE THE BEST POSSIBLE COURSE OF ACTION TO EMPTYING THE TRAILER PRIOR TO RIGHTING THE UNIT.  FORTUNATELY, THE ALUMINUM BARREL HAD REMAINED MOSTLY INTACT, WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE REAR TOP-RAILS HAVING BEEN IMPALED BY ONE OF THE GUARD RAIL SEGMENTS.  NO PRODUCT APPEARED TO HAVE ESCAPED THROUGH THAT SECTION OF THE BARREL.  AFTER EMERGENCY RESPONDERS SECURED THE SITE AND DEMOLISHED THE REMAINS OF THE BOATHOUSE, A COMPANY MECHANIC WAS DEPLOYED TO DRIL
column169: FROM BOTH AN OPERATIONAL AND SAFETY PERSPECTIVE, LYKINS TRANSPORATION, INC;  DOES HOLD QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS WITH OUR DRIVERS IN ORDER TO REVIEW A VARIETY OF DRIVING AND ROADWAY CONCERNS WITH OUR LINE OF BUSINESS.  ALL DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED IN PROPER ACTIVITIES, INCLUDING BEING ABLE TO PROTECT ONESELF FROM INCIDENTS THAT COULD OCCUR AT ANY GIVEN MOMENT.  DRIVERS ARE ENCOURAGED TO REPORT TO THEIR SUPERVISOR IF THEY FEEL THERE IS AN ISSUE WITH THEIR SCHEDULING OR WORKLOAD.    LYKINS TRANPORTATION, INC. REVIEWS ALL ACCIDENTS TO DETERMINE WHETHER OR NOT SUCH ACCIDENTS OR INCIDENTS COULD BE AVOIDED.  IN THIS INSTANCE, LYKINS TRANSPORTATION, INC; HAS MADE THE DETERMINATION THAT THE DRIVER COULD HAVE REASONABLY MADE THE EFFORT TO AVOID THE CONSEQUENCEES OF FATIQUE BEHIND THE WHEEL, AND FAILED TO DO SO AT THE COST OF HIS OWN SAFETY.  WHILE WE ARE PLEASED THAT THE DRIVER ESCAPED WITH ONLY MINOR INJURIES, LYKINS TRANSPORTATION, INC. HAS TERMINATED THE DRIVER'S EMPLOYMENT WITH THE COMPANY.    DURING OUR NEXT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING, OUR DRIVERS WILL BE BRIEFED ON THE INCIDENT, AS WELL AS THE CONSEQUENCES OF THE EMPLOYEE'S ACTIONS.  THE DRIVERS WILL ONCE MORE BE INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT THEIR SUPERVISOR IF THE DRIVER FEELS UNSAFE FOR ANY REASON, AND THEY WILL BE PRESENTED WITH THE EXPECTATION THAT A FAILURE TO PROTECT THEMSELVES WHILE ON THE ROADWAY WILL BE THOROUGHLY INVESTIGATED AND ACTED UPON.

column168: At approximately 1345 MT on 8/18/2015 a Clean Harbors Environmental services Inc. power unit and semi roll off trailer carrying one 30 yard intermodal container was travelling southbound on Colorado state highway 71. At approximate mile marker 183.5 the vehicle’s right front steer tire left the roadway and entered the soft shoulder causing the power unit and semi trailer to lose control and overturn onto the vehicle’s right side. The loss of control and subsequent rollover collision caused the semi trailer’s intermodal container to become unsecured. The intermodal container's contents were released as a result of the vehicle rollover accident. An emergency response team was summoned, donned the proper personal protective equipment, and remediated the release. The released material was reloaded and transported to the intended disposal facility. NRC report  #21966. Colorado Dept of Public Health & Environment operator Anne Nedrow provided report #2015-0537.
column169: Counsel the driver on the importance of being attentive to and aware of road conditions at all times and operating the vehicle in the safest, distraction free manner that conditions allow. Disciplinary action per Clean Harbors' TC 2.1 Disciplinary Guidelines is pending.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the storage phase of the operation, plant personnel inspects the trailers as part of their everyday activities.  During this type of inspection, it was discovered a few drops of black liquid near the front of the van trailer.  Absorbent material was applied to the spilled material.  A decision was made to move the trailer to the loading dock (which was lined with 6 mil poly) so as to be placed in containment area.   Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.  In house Field Services group was notified and dispatched to the plant. It was noted that a stacked pallet of 4 drums on top of the drums most likely resulted in the compromising of the seam on the two drums that leaked.  All absorbent and spill debris was placed in the over pack drum and secured for shipment to the designated treatment facility.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of compromise. IN addition, double stacking will be reviewed and discussed prior to loading.

column168: On 08/20/15 at 1335 hours CSXT yard personnel at the Montgomery Yard terminal located at 1250 Louisville Street Montgomery, AL discovered GAMX5483, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide, leaking from a weld seam in the jacket on the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Westlake C A + O, was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the product leaking from a weld seam in the jacket on the bottom of the car.  It was determined that there was no way to ensure the integrity of tank. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Doug Harris) who gave permission to CSXT and Hepaco to conduct an emergency field transfer of the product. Hepaco completed the emergency field transfer and a clean and purge on the car.    NAR Cause Code: 658  Tank/ Jacketed car/ Cause undetermined    2(2+3+5) x (2+0) = 120 NARRI     Montgomery, Alabama  08/20/15  GAMX5483  Sodium Hydroxide

column168: On August 20, 2015 at 11:40 hours personnel in the CSXT Erwin Yard discovered NATX 303538, a loaded tank car of Alcohol NOS leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Renewable Products Marketing Group, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2015-08-20-00150.  Joseph McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was on the scene and found the car was leaking from the vacuum relief valve and the treaded connection of the vapor line valve to the tank car.  The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Keith Krueger).  Marion Environmental, a CSX response contractor, was mobilized to make temporary securements to the car: the vacuum relief valve was removed and replaced with 2.5 pipe plug and the threaded connection of the vapor valve was tightened.  The car was held out of transportation pending mobile repair and requalification of the faulty service equipment and/or an OTMA.       NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause Code: 361, 1057  .
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 08/26/15 at 1346 hours CSXT yard personnel at the CSXT Sibert Yard terminal located at 2000 Industrial Canal Road East Mobile, AL discovered TCIX30022, a loaded tank car of Fuel Oil, that leaked from the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Universal Environmental Services, was notified. United States Environmental Services (USES), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product covering the top and sides of the car trailing from the area of the manway.  Further inspection revealed that all eight manway bolts were unsecured with 3 swing bolts hanging and the remaining 5 less than tool tight.  The manway gasket was also found to be cracked. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Patrick King). USES replaced the manway gasket, secured the manway, and cleaned the outside of the car.    NAR Cause Code: 200  Manway/ Hinged/ Bolts- Bolts/nuts less than tool tight    5(5+3+1) x (2+0) = 90 NARRI     Mobile, Alabama  08/26/15  TCIX30022  Fuel Oil

column168: On 08/30/15 at 1745 hours CSXT yard personnel at the CSXT Sibert Yard terminal located at 2000 Industrial Canal Rd E Mobile, AL discovered CPDX582145, a loaded tank car of Molten Sulphur, that was actively leaking from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated, the yard evacuated in that area, and the shipper, Chevron Corp, was notified. All CSXT personnel sheltered in place, the yard was shutdown, and the CSXT mainline was shutdown. United States Environmental Services (USES) and SWS Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. CSXT Hazmat Field Manager Trent Page responded. Further inspection revealed that the car was actively leaking from the PRD assembly due to corrosion and damage to the seat around the rupture disk.  One of the three bolts on the PRD assembly was also loose. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Billy Burrell). USES, SWS, and Trent Page replaced PRD rupture disk, the gasket, applied Teflon tape, and tightened the PRD assembly.  The leak was temporarily secured.  On 08/31/15 the shipper dispatched Freight Car and the PRD top assembly was replaced.  The leak remained secured.    NAR Cause Code: 1008  Non-reclosing pressure relief device/ broken    5(5+3+1) x (2+4) = 270 NARRI     Mobile, AL  08/30/15  CPDX582145-Molten Sulphur
column169: Ensure proper outbound inspections and consider replacement of older PRD assemblies.

column168: Note that details surrounding this incident are limited and this report was completed with information known.  The vehicle involved in this incident was actually a pup trailer which carried primarily water and had a small tank of JetA fuel for helicopters utilized within its area.  It is estimated that up to 500 gallons was on board by judging from the size of the tank.  The vehicle was travelling down a remote road and overturned resulting in a release of ~30 gallons of JetA fuel from the top of the tank.  The released fuel entered into the soils adjacent to the area of the accident.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal it was discovered that the tote had a small puncture hole in the bottom. After further investigation it was determined that the tote may have been punctured during the loading process at the origin terminal. The small puncture hole was immediately patched to prevent further release. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be retrieved.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had further caution been taken while loading the tote into the trailer. This incident may be used in future training discussions to discuss the importance of proper freight handling.

column168: Upon arrival at the relay terminal, a drum was found leaking inside of the trailer. Investigation revealed that the drum appeared to have been gouged by something. The pallet was examined and no protruding nails were found. It is possible the drum was punctured during the loading process at the origin terminal. The drum was immediately placed into an overpack along with absorbent materials. due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This release may have been prevented had there been dunnage placed to protect it during transit. This incident may be used as an example during dock meetings to show the importance of placing proper dunnage to protect freight.

column168: One 275 gallon tote containing UN1805 Phosphoric Acid was discovered cracked from an apparent load shift resulting in an estimated 20 gallons of material to be released to the trailer and asphalt parking lot. A contractor responded and conducted a tote transfer and the release was cleaned up using granular absorbents. All waste generated was taken with the contractor in containerized drums and bags and the replacement tote was sent on with shipment.

The driver delivered his load of gasoline to the store directly next to the store he was supposed to unload at. He then failed to check the tank levels before he started putting fuel in the ground. He began unloading and product began overfilling the tank because he was unloading into a full of fuel.
column169: The driver failed to follow SOP while unloading gasoline. The dispatcher told the driver the load would fit into the correct tank and the driver went to the wrong store and did not verify the tanks or his location.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Rack at loading facility failed to shut down at the amount of product our driver entered into their system, overfilling a compartment on our trailer.
column169: System error at loading facility.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Interior
column168: When the tank car was moved in the yard the crew observed smoke coming from the top of the car. It was inspected and there was a hole in the steel tank top of the car where vapor was releasing. There was a hole somewhere in the liner, the hole on the tank was patched and the car was offloaded without incident
column169: Proper inspection of car prior to and upon load, unload, and release for transport.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 3 gallons of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in a container. While accessing the compromised package, it was discovered a tote had been punctured by the corner of a light fixture, which was next to the tote while in transit.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place liquid from the compromised container into suitable drums. The bladder of the tote was placed in a flex-bin.  The light fixtures were placed in a flex-bin. In addition, the under carriage of the trailer and the floor of the trailer was decontaminated. The soil beneath the trailer was dug up (about 2' down) and placed in 8 flex-bins.  All personal protective equipment, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the flex-bins. Once complete, the containers were secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: Plant Manager's recommendations to prevent recurrence include:       Ship pcb containers direct to the end facility        Place all light fixtures in boxes to avoid corner edges from coming        into contact with adjacent packages

column168: Driver failed to open the belly valve while loading and the hose ruptured spilling 12 gallons of crude oil.

On Wednesday August 26 2015 at approximately 1030 AM EST a CHAT of Michigan employee was loading Halterman Solutions Ref No. 803490-2 consisting of 80 x 55 gallon drums of Gasoline UN 1203 into 40 Ft Ocean Container No. DFSU694069-1 at CHAT of Michiagn’s location at 35790 Northline Road, Romulus, MI 48174, and inadvertently punctured One (1) x 55 gallon drum of Product TR2127 with a fork of the forklift inside the container.     The employee was not aware that the forks of the forklift were protruding approximately 2” from the back-side of the pallet he was loading and had the pallet he was loading lifted too high, so that one of the protruding forks punctured the drum behind the pallet he was loading. The hole in the drum is appx 3" L x 1" W on the lower-side of the drum. CHAT immediately removed the damaged drum and all other undamaged material from the container, contained the spilled gasoline in the container, then began clean-up of the spilled gasoline inside the container using absorbent (vermiculite). We wrapped the damaged empty drum in a 4 mil think plastic containment bag, placed the damaged drum in a UN certified containment salvage drum, swept up the vermiculite after it had absorbed the spilled gasoline and place it in a separate UN certified containment salvage drum, and quarantined the container in our yard to air out.     In the meantime CHAT also immediately contacted the appropriate authorities (local FAA field office, local Romulus MI Fire Department), and also the shipper (Halterman Solutions) to notify them of the situation, and also immediately filed an Incident Report with the Shipper's 24 Hour Emergency Contact Provider Service Chemtrec (Report ID No.: 2015082600116)     The Ocean Line agreed to accept the Ocean Container back into service on Sept 2 2015 after it had aired out at CHAT for 7 days since there were no gasoline fumes or damage to the floor of the container, so container was re-loaded with 79 drums and shipped from CHAT on Sept 3 2015.     CHAT of Michigan’s internal review has resulted in the employee being terminated for failure to follow company loading policies.
column169: CHAT of Michigan immediately re-trained and re-tested the employee and all other warehouse employees on Fork Lift Safety and loading procedures the same afternoon August 26 2015.

An ISO tank was pulled off of a rail car and found to have a very small amount of material released from what was believed to be a missing washout cap. A rail certified environmental contractor responded to the incident and discovered a valve on top of the tank to not be secured properly. Approximately 1 quart of the material leaked to the outside of the container. The valve was resecured and any residual product that had not evaporated was wiped up. After the tank was reassessed it was staged for continued transport.

CARRIER DRIVER AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION AND SET UP TO HAVE THE TRACTOR MOUNTED PUMP SUPPLY THE POWER TO MOVE THE CARGO INTO THE CONSIGNEE STORAGE TANK.  AFTER TRACTOR PUMP WAS STARTED, THE CONSIGNEE HOSE BURST.  CONSIGNEE DISCOVERED THAT THEY HAD NOT OPENED THEIR INTAKE VALVE ON THEIR STORAGE TANK.  FOLLOWING  THE REPLACEMENT OF THE CONSIGNEE TRANSFER HOSE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A LOOSE FITTING ON THE CARRIER'S TRACTOR PUMP WAS LEAKING INTO A BUCKET UNDER IT.  CONSIGNEE AND CARRIER'S DRIVER MONITORED THE LEAK WHILE OFFLOADING PROCEEDED.  A TOTAL OF 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  CONSIGNEE CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF SPILLED PRODUCT.  CARRIER'S TRACTOR PUMP HAD BEEN NEWLY INSTALLED AND THIS WAS THE FIRST LOAD USING IT.  CARRIER'S MECHANIC DETERMINED THAT THE FITTINGS HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY TIGHTENED DURING INITIAL INSTALLATION.  PUMP FITTINGS WERE REMOVED, INSPECTED AND RE-INSTALLED PROPERLY.    EVENT #47370

column168: ON 8-8-15, A SERVICE TRANSPORT TANKER TRUCK VEERED FROM THE ROADWAY COMING TO AN UPRIGHT STOP AT THE PROPERTY LOCATED AT 1689 GRAEFENBURG ROAD IN LAWRENCEBURG, KY. THE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN A GASOLINE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 482 GALLONS FROM A PUNCTURE IN THE WALL OF THE TANKER (PASSENGER SIDE/UPPER PORTION). NEARBY HOMES WERE EVACUATED BY FIRST RESPONDERS, INITIAL CONTAINMENT PROCEDURES WERE EMPLOYED BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE HIGHWAY WAS SHUT DOWN BY THE LOCAL SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT. ONCE THE REMAINDER OF PRODUCT ON THE WRECKED TANKER WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANKER ON-SITE, THE WRECKED TANKER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE VIA TOW TRUCK. AT THIS POINT, THE HIGHWAY WAS REOPENED AND SOUTHERN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES BEGAN REMEDIATION OF THE SPILL SITE.  USING A TRACK EXCAVATOR, GASOLINE IMPACTED AREAS WERE REMOVED AND STAGED ONTO PLASTIC SHEETING. THE EXCAVATION PIT WAS SAMPLED FOR CONSTITUENTS OF GASOLINE AND BACKFILLED FROM A STOCKPILE OF SOIL LOCATED ON THE PROPERTY WITH PERMISSION FROM THE PROPERTY OWNER.  THE EXCAVATED WASTE MATERIAL (477.67 TONS) WAS TRANSPORTED TO HARDIN COUNTY LANDFILL ON THE DAYS FOLLOWING THE EXCAVATION VIA DUMP TRUCKS.  LASTLY, THE SITE WAS RESTORED WITH SEED AND STRAW MATTING.
column169: AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION OF PRACTICES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT ARE CURRENTLY BEING EXPLORED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. LEAK WAS DISCOVERED DURING UNLOADING AT THE N&M TRANSFER FACILITY. TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND RESPONSE WAS COORDINATED. ENVIROMARK WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSESS AND PERFORM CLEANUP. UPON INSPECTION, ONE 300-GALLON TOTE WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED, DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND DID NOT IMPACT THE GROUND SURFACE OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. ENVIROMARK NEUTRALIZED THE FREE PRODUCT, AND WIPED ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WITHIN DAMAGED TOTE WAS PUMPED INTO A RECOVERY TOTE. TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED TO DRY OUT THE CONTAMINATED FREIGHT AND VENTILATE TRAILER. NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT AND CLEANUP DEBRIS WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.
column169: N&M TRANSFER WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

ALL EFFORTS WHERE TAKEN TO CONTAIN PRODUCT SUCH AS BOOMS, SPILL PROS, OIL DRY AND ETC.

column168: THE DRIVER COMPLETED THE TRANSFER OF A MIXED ACID WASTE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S ON-SITE STORAGE TANKS TO THE ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA TANKER TRUCK. UPON COMPLETION OF PAPERWORK, THE TRUCK WAS CLEARED TO LEAVE THE SITE. UPON MAKING AN INCLINED STOP AT A STOPLIGHT THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TANKER. AT THE SAME TIME, A PASSENGER VEHICLE ALSO NOTICED THE LEAK AND ALERTED THE DRIVER. AS SOON AS SAFELY POSSIBLE, THE DRIVER PULLED OFF OF THE THOROUGHFARE, ACCESSED THE SPILL KIT TO IMMEDIATELY BLOCK OFF NEARBY STORM DRAIN AND THEN DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK. MEANWHILE, THE DRIVER OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE ASSISTED THE DRIVER AND CALLED 911 TO NOTIFY LOCAL AUTHORITIES OF THE INCIDENT. UPON INSPECTION, HE NOTICED THAT THE FRONT HATCH DOME LID HAD BEEN CLOSED BUT NOT FULLY SECURED PRIOR TO LEAVING THE CUSTOMER SITE. AS HE UNLATCHED THE DOME COVER, HE FOUND A METAL ROOFING BOLT LODGED BETWEEN THE HINGE PREVENTING THE HATCH AND TO SEAL PROPERLY. HE REMOVED THE OBSTRUCTION, PROPERLY CLOSED AND SEALED THE FRONT HATCH AND PREVENTED ANY FURTHER LEAKS.
column169: HUMAN ERROR WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT. ADDITIONAL COMMUNICATION TO DRIVERS REGARDING INSPECTION OF ALL SEALS PRIOR TO CLOSING THE CARGO TANKER HATCHES HAS BEEN COMPLETED.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS STOPPED BECAUSE IT WAS SUSPICIOUS. THE BOXES HAD UNSPECIFIED MARKING AND THEY WERE NOT DECLARED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOXES CONTAINED PERFUME AND WERE HELD. I NOTIFIED LORI LUSCHER OF THE SEA / FAA TO ADVISE OF THE INCIDENT AT 12:50 ON 8-28-2015. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR THEIR INVESTIGATION. I MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER WHO STATED SHE DIDN'T KNOW WHAT WAS IN THE PACKAGES. I LATER RECEIVED AN EMAIL FROM ONE OF HER CO-WORKERS IN NY TO DISCUSS. I WAS LATER PUT IN TOUCH WITH JOE DEROCHE OF THE SEA / FAA FOR FURTHER FOLLOW UP AS HE HAD INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT AS WELL. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND LATER PACKED UP BY THE SHIPPER.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS DRIVING UP BIRCHFIELD AVE MT LAUREL WHEN A VEHICLE OCCUPIED WITH TWO SENIOR CITIZEN WAS ABOUT TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN INTO A DRIVEWAY AT THE LAST MINUTE. THEY CHANGED THEIR MIND AND DROVE RIGHT BACK INTO TRAFFIC. IN ORDER TO AVOID THE CAR OUR DRIVER TRIED TO TURN INTO A SIDE STREET AND DID NOT MAKE IT. THE OTHER DRIVER WAS CITED WITH A DRIVING VIOLATION AND WE RECEIVED NONE. PACKAGE FAILURE WAS MINOR RUPTURE IN REAR BUCKHEAD AND MOST OUT OF TANK LID. DURATION OF RELEASE ABOUT 45 MIN. ALL EFFORT WHEN TAKEN TO CONTAIN PRODUCT SUCH AS BOOMS, SPILL PADS, OIL DRY ETC.
column169: BASICALLY WE ADDED THIS AS A EXAMPLE IN OUR MONTHLY SAFETY MEETINGS. WE ARE ALSO ADDING DIGITAL VIDEO IN ALL COMPANY VEHICLES SO WE CAN OBSERVE DRIVING PRACTICES.

column168: A 55 GALLON METAL DRUM CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE, FLAMMABLE TOXIC LIQUID (ETHYL ETHER/CHLOROFORM) WAS PUNCTURED WITH THE FORKLIFT TINE WHILE TRYING TO OFFLOAD WASTE FROM A TRAILER. THE SAFE DRAIN HAD THE LIQUID REMOVED, RINSED AND WIPED DOWN WITH SIMPLE GREEN.

column168: A RAIL CAR OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS BEING UNLOADED INTO A STORAGE TANK. THE TANK WAS OVERFILLED AND MATERIAL FLOWED INTO A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE. A SUMP PUMP USED FOR REMOVING RAINWATER WAS LEFT IN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE AND WHEN THE FLOAT SWITCH ON THE PUMP ACTIVATED THE MATERIAL WAS PUMPED OUT OF CONTAINMENT ONTO A CONCRETE SURFACE. THE MATERIAL FLOWED NORTH THROUGH A GRAVEL LOT TO THE STORM SEWER GRATE LOCATED IN THE SE CORNER OF EDWIN ST NW AND STERLING AVE NW. A PORTION OF THE MATERIAL FLOWED WEST THROUGH THE STORM SEWER SYSTEM TO WILL AVE. NW, THEN SOUTH TO ANN ST. NW, AND WAS DISCHARGED TO INDIAN MILL CREEK. THE VOLUME OF MATERIAL RELEASED WAS DETERMINED BY MASS BALANCE (ATTACHED). ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE IS BELIEVED TO BE MINIMAL AS PH READINGS IN INDIAN MILL CREEK ~30 FEET DOWNSTREAM OF THE DISCHARGE WERE MEASURED AT 6-7 PH (PER CARRIE RIVETTE- CITY OF GRAND RAPIDS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES). HAVILAND’S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED, AS WELL AS THE CITY OF GRAND RAPIDS FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE DEPARTMENT, CITY OF GRAND RAPIDS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, AND SET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. MATERIAL WAS DIKED ONSITE AND COLLECTED AS WELL AS MATERIAL FROM THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE. THE CITY OF GRAND RAPIDS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DEPARTMENT INSTALLED A STORM SEWER PLUG AT THE CORNER OF ANN ST. NW AND WILL AVE. NW TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL CONTAINMENT AND ALSO PROVIDED SAND BAGS FROM THE HAVILAND HAZMAT TEAM TO PROVIDE CONTAINMENT FOR THE STORM SEWER DISCHARGE. THE STORM SEWER INLET ORIGINALLY IMPACTED AND THE SAND BAGGED AREA AT THE STORM SEWER DISCHARGE WAS PUMPED. THEN WITH THE HELP OF THE GRFD A HYDRANT WAS USED TO WASH DOWN THE SPILL AREA TO THE STORM SEWER. A VACUUM TRUCK WAS STATIONED AT THE STORM SEWER PLUG TO CAPTURE ALL OF THE WASH DOWN WATER. THE VOLUME OF WASH WATER FOR EACH FLUSH WAS LIMITED TO 1500 GALLONS TO ENSURE CAPACITY IN THE VACUUM TRUCK. THE STORM SEWER WAS FLUSHED TWICE WITH WATER, AND TWO MORE TIMES WITH WATER AND 40 GALLONS OF LIQUID CITRIC ACID (EACH TIME) TO NEUTRALIZE ANY RESIDUAL SODIUM HYDROXIDE IN THE STORM SEWER AFTER THE FOURTH FLUSH THE PH IN THE STORM SEWER WAS MEASURED AT 5.5. THE STORM SEWER PLUG WAS THEN REMOVED. THE NEXT MORNING, 08/12/2015 AT 7:25 AM, THE WATER AT THE STORM WATER DISCHARGE WAS MEASURED AGAIN AND SHOWED IT TO BE 7.5. THE SAND BAGS WERE REMOVED FROM INDIAN MILL CREEK AT 05:1 AM THAT MORNING AND TREATED INTERNALLY FOR ANY RESIDUAL SODIUM HYDROXIDE. WATER AT THE STORM SEWER DISCHARGE WAS MEASURED AGAIN ON 08/13/2015 AT 10:00AM WITH A RESULT OF 8.6 PH, AND 08/14/2015 AT 4:00 PM WITH A RESULT OF 7 PH.     THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE.  NOTE: SECTION 28 – “PROVIDE PACKAGING CONSTRUCTION AND TEST INFORMATION, AS APPROPRIATE” – HAVILAND ENTERPRISES, INC. DOES NOT OWN THE RAIL CAR INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT AND DOES NOT HAVE THE RAIL CAR CONSTRUCTION DETAILS.
column169: STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR UNLOADING RAIL CARS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE HAVE BEEN UPDATED TO INCLUDE ACCURATE VOLUMES OF THE STORAGE TANKS. column168: DRIVER CONNECTED TO THE CUSTOMER TANK AND BEGAN THE AIR PROCESS TO THE PUMP TO BEGIN OFFLOADING. HE TURNED ON THE PUMP AND BEGAN OFFLOADING. column169: DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND ALERTED THE CUSTOMER. ABSORBENT MATS WERE USED TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE ALUM THAT SPILLED ON THE DRIVEWAY. APPROXIMATELY 3-4 GALLONS WERE LOST. THE DRIVEWAY WAS THEN WASHED OFF DOWN TO THE CHEMICAL SUMP. DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW ESTABLISHED PROCEDURE OF CHECKING ALL VALVES BEFORE OFFLOADING. EMPLOYEE FITNESS IS A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR, DRIVER STATED HE WAS TIRED BY THE END OF THE DAY WHEN THIS DELIVERY TOOK PLACE. OFFLOADING PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED AND DISCIPLINARY ACTION NOTIFICATION WILL BE GIVEN TO DRIVER.

column168: DRIVER WAS FILLING A 405 TANK AT GE. THE TANK CONTAINED 230 GALLONS BASED ON TELEMETRY AND DRIVER OFFLOADED 231 GALLONS BASED ON THE TRAILER FLOW TOTALIZER. column169: THE PRODUCT WAS DILUTED WITH WATER BY FLUSHING TO THE CHEMICAL SUMP TANK. OFFLOADING PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED WITH DRIVER AND DISCIPLINARY ACTION NOTIFICATION WILL BE GIVEN. DRIVER OPENLY ADMITS TO NOT FOLLOWING THE REQUIRED PROCEDURE. DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW THE ESTABLISHED PROCEDURE FOR NON-LINE OF SITE TANKS AND FOR OFFLOADING CHEMICAL. DRIVER WAS NOT ATTENDING THE TRUCK BUT INSTEAD PICKING UP DRY MATE CAPS THEY HAD FOUND ON THE GROUNDS.

column168: CUSTOMER TANK PIPING SYSTEM DURING THE DELIVERY. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE UNLOADING IMMEDIATELY ON DISCOVERING THE LEAK AND DISCONTINUED THE DELIVERY. DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH TO REPORT THE LEAK AND THE CUSTOMER WAS PLACED ON SAFETY HOLD. column169: DRIVER FOLLOWED PROCEDURE EXACTLY AND PERFORMED AS TRAINED IN THIS INSTANCE. DRIVER WOULD HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO COMPLETELY PREVENT THE RELEASE SINCE HE HAD TO START FLOW BEFORE CHECKING FOR LEAKS. ONCE THE FLOW WAS STARTED, HE WALKED THE LINE ALL THE WAY TO THE CUSTOMER TANK WHERE THE LEAKING ELBOW WAS DISCOVERED. HE THEN RETURNED IMMEDIATELY TO HIS TRAILER AND STOPPED PRODUCT FLOW.

column168: DRIVER WAS FILLING THIS NEW TANK FOR THE FIRST TIME. THE DELIVERY STARTED NORMALLY AND DRIER STATED HE WAS FEEDING PRODUCT SLOWLY AS THIS WAS ALL NEW PIPING. THE FILL GAUGE SEEMED TO OPERATE CORRECTLY AT FIRST UP TO ABOUT THE 1/4 FULL MARK. DRIVER AND THE CUSTOMER NOTICED THE PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE GOING IN SLOWLY AS THE GAUGE WAS NOT MOVING FROM 1/4 FULL. DRIVER THEN CLAIMS HE SAW PRODUCT COMING OUT OF THE OVERFILL WHILE THE GAUGE STILL SHOWED 1\4 FULL.
column169: DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND CALLED CUSTOMER SERVICE AND MANAGER TO INFORM OF THE OVERFILL. PROCEDURES TO SHUT DOWN AT THE FIRST SIGN OF ANY ABNORMALITY WERE NOT FOLLOWED. WHEN INSPECTED AFTER THE OVERFILL, THE LEVEL GAUGE WAS SHOWN TO BE CORRECTLY READING THE TANK LEVEL.

column168: THIS IS A TANK THAT FILLS INFREQUENTLY AND WE FILLED IT RECENTLY. WHEN THE ORDER CAME IN WE QUESTIONED IF THIS WAS THE TANK AND PRODUCT THEY WANTED FILLED. IT APPEARS THE OVERFILL WAS APPROX. 500 LBS OF 30% CAUSTIC. THE CUSTOMER WAS WATCHING THE TANK LEVELS VIA THEIR OWN ELECTRONIC LEVEL MONITORING SYSTEM. THE MONITORING SYSTEM SHOULD HAVE INDICATED THE VOLUME OF THE TANK PRIOR TO FILL AND THE FULL LEVEL. THE TANK OVERFLOWED BEFORE THE LEVEL SYSTEM INDICATED A FULL TANK.
column169: CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED AND THEIR MONITORING SYSTEM REVIEWED. IT APPEARS THAT THE CUSTOMER EMPLOYEE MONITORING THE TANK LEVEL WAS NOT ATTENTIVE TO THE TASK AND FAILED TO COMMUNICATE TIMELY TO DRIVER.

column168: A TANKER WAS PUMPING DIESEL FUEL INTO A UST AT THE LAKEVIEW GROCERY FUEL STATION, WHEN A FIRE IGNITED UNDER THE HOOD OF THE VEHICLE (CAUSE UNKNOWN). ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO PUT OUT THE FIRE, BUT WHEN THE FIRE BEGAN TO SPREAD TO THE REST OF THE TANKER, THE AREA WAS EVACUATED. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE AND TOOK CHARGE. FIRE DEPARTMENT OFFICIALS SPRAYED WATER AND FOAM ON THE BURNING VEHICLE AND THEN ALLOWED THE TANKER TO BURN FOR SEVERAL HOURS BEFORE THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED. D’S EMERGENCY SERVICES VACUUMED THE TANKER’S REMAINING LIQUID (600 GALLONS) FOR OFF-SITE DISPOSAL. D’S ALSO SPRAYED AND BURNED SPILL AFFECTED GRAVEL PARKING AREA WITH MICRO BLAZE AND TREATED WITH ABSORBENTS. SUBSEQUENTLY, A GEOLOGIST WITH PMI ASSESSED THE EXTENT OF SPILL CONTAMINATION ON-SITE, AND THEN SUPERVISED EXCAVATION OF CONTAMINATED GAVEL ON-SITE. CONFIRMATORY SOIL SAMPLING OCCURRED AND THE SITE WAS BACKFILLED AND RESTORED. ALL WASTE REMOVED FROM THE SITE WAS DISPOSED OF AT LICENSED FACILITIES. A REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED TO THE OKDEQ.
column169: ALL TANK TRUCKS WERE INSPECTED FOR POTENTIAL ISSUES WITH COMBUSTION IN PROXIMITY TO CARGO TANK. THE FIRE ORIGINATED UNDER CAB OF TRUCK, SO THIS AREA WAS SCRUTINIZED FOR HEAT OR ELECTRICAL CONTACT WITH FUEL SOURCES THAT COULD POSE A DANGER. WE ALSO USE THIS INCIDENT WAS A CASE STUDY FOR OTHER DRIVERS. WE FEEL THAT THE DRIVER’S RESPONSE TO LIFE, THEN PROPERTY WAS APPROPRIATE AND STRIVE TO LEARN MORE FROM THE ACTIONS TAKEN

column169: REVIEWED CAUSAL ANALYSIS WITH DRIVER. PUBLISHED INCIDENT INTERNALLY TO INFORM OTHER DRIVERS, AS PART OF K COM'S SAFETY PROGRAM.

column168: AA3475 INBOUND FROM ORD ARRIVED AT GATE 82 IN MCI AT 1144 DURING THE OFFLOAD PROCESS OF THE VALET CHECK BAGS, PIEDMONT SUPERVISOR MATT TOLAND ENCOUNTERED A VALET BAG THAT WAS SMOKING AND HOT TO THE TOUCH. HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED ME TO ADVISE, AND I RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO GATE 82. I IMMEDIATELY CALLED AIRPORT POLICE AND LOOKING AT THE BAG. THERE WAS NO NAME ON THE VALET CHECKED TAG BUT THERE WAS AN OLD BINGO STICKER FROM A PREVIOUS TRIP, I TOOK THE BINGO STICKER AND WENT TO THE JET WAY WHERE THE PASSENGERS WERE WAITING AND CALLED OUT THE NAME ON THE BINGO STICKER STACEY WAGNER, ONE PASSENGER GREGORY RIFFLE CAME FORWARD.  I PULLED HIM ASIDE FROM ALL THE OTHER PASSENGERS AND ASKED FOR A DESCRIPTION OF HIS VALET CHECKED BAG, AND HE GAVE ME A DESCRIPTION OF THE BAG WE HAD. I ASKED IF HE HAD ANY E-CIGARETTES OR LITHIUM BATTERIES IN HIS BAG. HE RESPONDED THAT HE HAD A GARMIN GPS UNIT IN HIS BAG. I TOLD HIM THAT HIS BAG CAME OF THE PLANE SMOKING AND HOT TO TOUCH, AND THAT WE HAD CALLED THE AIRPORT POLICE TO CLEAR THE BAG BEFORE WE COULD HAND IT OVER TO HIM. HE REPLIED THAT HE UNDERSTOOD AND I ASKED HIM TO WAIT IN THE JET WAY. WHILE I WAS WITH THE PASSENGER AN AIRPORT POLICE OFFICER WAS DRIVING BY GATE 82, AND MATT HAD THE RAMP AGENTS FLAG DOWN OFFICER SANDY THOMPSON. I WAS RETURNING TO THE JET WAY AS HE WAS PULLING UP, I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION AND OFFICER THOMPSON BEFORE HE INSPECTED THE BAG AND ITS CONTENTS. JOHN LANE CONTACTED THE TSA COORDINATION CENTER WHILE OFFICER THOMPSON SEARCHED THE BAG. OFFICER THOMPSON CLEARED THE BAG AND WE WENT TO THE JET WAY FOR HIM TO QUESTION THE PASSENGER.

column168: Vehicle #1 (Pickup Truck) was at the bottom of the onramp of State Route (SR) 970 from Int. I-90.  Vehicle #2 (Our Tank Truck & Tank Trailer) was driving East down the SR 970 ramp from Int. I-90.  Vehicle #2 was behind Vehicle #1.  At the bottom of the ramp, Vehicle #1 attempted to make an illegal U-turn.  In doing so, Vehicle #1 turned directly in front of Vehicle #2.  The front of Vehicle #2 impacted the left side of Vehicle #1.  Vehicle #1 came to rest blocking the westbound lane of SR 970.  Vehicle #2 rolled, crossing both lanes of SR 970.  Vehicle #2 came to rest with the tank truck (tractor portion) perpendicular and blocking both lanes of SR 970.    The pull trailer came to rest, still attached to the tank truck, on the shoulder north of the roadway.  Vehicle #2 Tank Truck loaded with 5150 gallons of Regular Unleaded 87/w-ethanol gasoline caught fire and burned. The pull trailer was loaded with 4550 gallons of Regular Unleaded 87/w-ethanol gasoline and 1700 gallons of Premium Unleaded 92/w-ethanol gasoline.  Although the pull trailer rolled it stayed in tack and contained the gasoline only losing approximately 50-75 gallons out of one dome lid.

column168: Driver advised that the pump was running on his truck but the customer advised they weren't getting any product in their tank.  The driver felt the hose from the pump to the customer fill line and it felt light.  He verified there was product reaching the petcocks / primer valves on the pump.  He shut everything down including the pump and the valves on the truck and customer fill line.  He slowly released one of the camlocks and nothing came out so then he disconnected the other.  He lifted the hose trying to ensure nothing would spill and he said it must have burped an air bubble out and then product started coming up and over the top of the hose (which seems odd).  Only thing i can venture to guess is that when he shut down the pump still had vacuum pressure on the 'draw' side and when it was able to vent it used that vacuum to push the product into the outflow side of the pump.  When product started coming up and over is when he tried to reconnect the hose to prevent further spillage and when he did product splashed out and hit him in the chest area only.  He showered immediately and advised he was fine.  I followed up with him later to verify he was still not seeing any symptoms.  The driver didnt have the right PPE on for what we require, he was missing the nomex suit and also goggles.  I don't think that would've changed the overall outcome on this as the nomex isn't a chemical suit, it is just a flame retardent covering.  We believe this started as the customer tank vent wasn't opened and therefore product couldn't flow into the tank.  When we asked the customer they said they verified it was but no one ever went back on top of the customer tank to double check.  The same question was asked several times as a matter of fact and the same answer without anyone looking.  1 -2 quarts in total spilled.
column169: Driver should have used bleeder valve on his pump to bleed off any pressure on the line as well as any product that made it into the hose from the discharge side of his pump before disconnecting to inspect. Driver was brought in for training on this aspect as well as where to look for the appropriate PPE in his work assignments.  The driver continues to have no known health effects.

column168: The Sea Logix driver was on the WBCT Marine Terminal in California delivering a loaded Ecolab container PGHU401895-7 when he was struck by a top loader stacker causing damage to his tractor and the container.  The terminal staff notified the Port Police, Fire Department & Patriot Environmental (Hazardous Response Service for the terminal).  ChemTrec has been notified per your bill of lading contacts. The load was reworked, equipment cleaned and neutralized and the recouped product was placed in overpack packaging.
column169: The Sea Logix Driver and the terminal Yard Stacker operator both need to be educated on the requirements for safe driving on the marine terminal.  This incident could have been avoided had proper attention to the traffic patters and awareness training been understood by both equipment drivers.  The day was clear and dry with very good visibility.  This accident was caused by human error.

column168: AT APPROX. 11:55AM OUR DELIVERY PERSON ARRIVED AT “WASHRITE INC”. A PRESSURE WASHER COMPANY. THIS WAS OUR 1ST DELIVERY TO THIS NEW CUSTOMER, THE CUSTOMER PROVIDED A DRUM AND TOLD US TO FILL THE DRUM. THE DRIVE BEGAN TO POUR SODIUM INTO CUSTOMERS DRUM AND THERE WAS AN IMMEDIATE CHEMICAL REACTION CAUSING THE DRUM TO EXPLODE. THE EXPLOSION CAUSED FUME AND INJURY TO OUR DRIVER’S LEG. 4 OFFICE PEOPLE AND OUR DRIVER WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL.
column169: THE DRIVER HAD JUST ATTENDED A COMPANY SAFETY MEETING ADDRESSING, PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT ON 7/8/15. THE DRIVER HAD THE EQUIPMENT WITH HIM BUT DID NOT USE IT. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WE HELD ANOTHER TRAINING SESSION THAT ADDRESSES LOOKING AT CONTAINED, SMELLING TO MAKE SURE NO CHEMICAL MIXES OCCUR AND ANOTHER REVIEW OF PERSONAL PROTECTION USE (AGENDA ENCLOSED). WE ALSO REMINDED ALL DELIVERY PERSONS OF OUR SECOND LOOK PROGRAM ALSO NOTED ON THE AGENDA.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: THE DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS AND PACKAGE FAILURE:    DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD OF APPROXIMATELY 8,000 GALLONS OF 87 E10 GASOLINE FROM BUCKEYE ROUGE, 205 MARION AVE RIVER ROGUE, MI 48218 (SEE ATTACHED BOL) AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00AM ON THE MORNING OF AUGUST 20TH, 2015. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO HEAD TOWARDS HIS NEXT DELIVERY DESTINATION. HIS ROUTE OF TRAVEL PLACED HIM ON THE SOUTH BOUND I75 FREEWAY. THE WEATHER AT THE TIME WAS AN EXTREME DOWNPOUR OF RAIN. ACCORDING TO THE ATTACHED POLICE REPORT, THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING IN THE CENTER LANE OF THE SOUTHBOUND I75 FREEWAY, SOUTH OF SCHAEFFER RD. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO CHANGE LANES, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE TRUCK DUE TO THE WET ROAD CONDITIONS. THE SEMI-TRUCK WENT LEFT AND DROVE THROUGH THE MEDIAN WALL. THE SEMI-TRUCK OVERTURNED IN THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF THE I75 FREEWAY AND CAUGHT FIRE, TRAPPING THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO DETROIT RECEIVING HOSPITAL. DRIVER SUCCUMBED TO HIS INJURIES AND PASSED AWAY LATER IN THE DAY.     AS FOR THE PACKAGE FAILURE AND ENSUING SPILL AND ACTION TAKEN TO MITIGATE THE EFFECT OF THE RELEASE. FIRST OF ALL THE TANKER FAILED TO THE IMPACT AND EVENTUAL ROLL OVER THE FREEWAY MEDIAN WALL. THE CRASH CREATED A SPARK CAUSING THE FUEL CONTENTS TO CATCH FIRE. THE ACCIDENT WAS REPORTED BY WITNESSES TO THE AUTHORITIES WHO DISPATCHED POLICE AND FIRE CRES TO THE SCENE. FIRE CREWS DID THEIR PART TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND FIRE; THEY UTILIZED FLOOR DRY AS WELL AS WATER AND FOAM TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. AS SOON AS CORRIGAN WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT THEY IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY COMPANY “TERRA CONTRACTING” AND DISPATCHED THEM TO THE SCENE. AS SOON AS THEY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE THEY TOOK OVER ALL ASPECTS OF THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP OF THE SPILL (SEE TERRA’S ATTACHED REPORT FOR FURTHER DETAILS).    ALSO WE HAVE ATTACHED A FEW PHOTOS FROM THE SCENE FOR FURTHER VISUAL CLARIFICATION OF DAMAGE.

column168: Jacob Turner, checker, was working Trailer 68601. He went to remove 2 decking beams located above the Hazmat PRO that was leaking, 075499510, when he felt a wet substance on his arm. He then noticed that there was a leak at the top of the container at which time he contacted the reporting supervisor, James Meek, about the incident. I informed the employee to immediately wash his arm to remove the substance. An injury report was later filed due to minor skin irritation. The employee was informed to seek medical assistance and contact us, if it worsens. ~~I then blocked off the area and notified Safety and Security. We were informed by Brian Schutte to either find an employee willing to clean the spill or contact a hazmat spill team. We were told to use gloves, goggles, and to dispose of material in a salvage drum. Also, to use stay dry to clean up the small amount on the floor of the trailer. ~~During clean up, it was noticed that portions of the gasket on the lid were inside of the tank. It appears that the gasket may have failed due to being improperly applied to the top of the tote, resulting in some of the contents being released through the lid (approx 1 cup). We have put the gasket back in place, resealed the lid, and cleaned the inside of the trailer.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure that the gasket is in place and properly maintained to prevent further spills. Portions of the gasket were visibly not in place under the lid and protruding from the tensioned side of the lid. Driver performing pickup could also do an inspection, although it might not be as easy for him to see flaws in packaging due to the height of this container (approx 6').~~Checkers need to be aware of surroundings. Pre-shift briefs will use this incident as a learning tool to try to prevent further incidents. Make sure that checkers are visually ensuring there isn't leaks to hazmat containers before working around the freight.~~

column168: During coupling operations and employee was "splashed" with contents (sulfuric acid) from GATX 7463. Employee was decontaminated on site and sought additional medical treatment (treated and released). Upon inspection it was discover that the fill hole was sealed properly. The bolts were tool tight but the "safety swing bolt" was positioned in a way that prevented the fill hole from being seated against the gasket. This condition was rectified, the car decontaminated, and shipped to destination without further incident.
column169: The loading facility has been contacted and have put additional steps in place to ensure this will not happen again.

column168: On August 29, 2015, at 05:06 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Parkersburg Yard, Parkersburg, West Virginia reported that a chlorine odor was reported around AXLX 1456, a residue tank car of UN1017, Chlorine. Reportedly, there was evidence of discoloration around the protective housing. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Clearon Corp, was notified via Chemtrec, report # 2015-0829-00030. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Parkersburg Yard. Matt Bond, (304) 266-8287 from the Consignee Axial was contacted for local CHLOREP Team. SPSI found that the PRD was in fact releasing product and would need to be capped with a "C" kit as the tank car only had 129 psi. CSX contacted local FRA Hazmat Dan McCourt who alerted FRA Region 2 that an emergency move would need to take place and return the tank car to Axial Facility in Natrium, WV. CSX arranged for a special train move that would have air monitoring equipment on board and the "C" kit would be checked periodically to ensure the leak remained contained. Once returned to Axial the tank car would be depressurized and appropriate repairs would be made. AXLX 1456 was handed off to Axial at 17:15.     NARRI: 5x(4+10+2)x(2+7) = 720  Cause code:702
